               <interp inst="t18440205-813" type="date" value="18440205"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440205-813-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-813-18440205 t18440205-813-offence-1 t18440205-813-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>813. <persName id="def1-813-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-813-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-813-18440205" type="age" value="24"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-813-18440205" type="surname" value="GRIFFITHS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-813-18440205" type="given" value="GRIFF"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GRIFF GRIFFITHS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440205-813-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440205-813-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440205-813-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, 3 washhnd-stands, value 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18440205-name-1561" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1561" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1561" type="surname" value="PRICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1561" type="given" value="ROBERT JAMES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440205-813-offence-1 t18440205-name-1561"></join>Robert James Price</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1562" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1562" type="surname" value="PRICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1562" type="given" value="ROBERT JAMBS"></interp>ROBERT JAMBS PRICE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Margaret-street, Haggerston, and am a cabinet-maker. The prisoner was my journeyman—I paid hin 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, with his board, lodging, and washing—I had three wash hand-stands in Oct, last—on the 27th of Oct., there was a knock at the door—I sent my sister-in-law down to answer it—she said it was a person named Henley who wanted Griffiths—the prisoner then went, and was gone three quarters of an hour—when he returned, I said, "Who was that?"—he said, "Mr. Henley who came to tell me where to soil the stands, ever the water"—oa the 28th the prisoner and I went to sell die stands over the water—when we got there he said, "This is the shop, it is a man that knowa me well, and has takes money of my father; if you like I will take them in and sell them"—he took them, and I said, "Don't sell them for less than three sovereigns, they are worth 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. "—he was there for two hours, and then came out—he said he had sold them for 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; but I must wait till six o'clock tor the money—he got off, and went home to my residence, and told my brother to go to Mott and Griffin's (which I had told the prisoner to tell him)—I did not see the prisoner again till he was taken about five weeks ago—Mr. Reed showed me the receipt for 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for the washhand-stands—this is it—it is the pri<lb></lb>soner's writing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Can you say I was no partner of yours? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I can.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050234"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> Here is a card (<hi rend="italic">producing one with</hi> "<hi rend="italic">G. Griffith and Price</hi>" <hi rend="italic">on it</hi>) which you desired me to get printed; here is my name first on the card. <hi rend="italic">Hiness.</hi> I know nothing of this card—here is my card, with my name only on it—I neither ordered nor paid for the others.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did you not go with me to Mr. Breton's when we drew two bills on him, I put my name first? he asked you whether it was true that I was partner with you, and you said, "Yes;" there is Mr. Breton in Court now; you signed your name under mine? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is totally false—when the prisoner came to me he said he had not had a meal for two days, nor a lodg<lb></lb>ing for two nights—I lodged and boarded him two days, and two nights, and on the third day he asked me to give him a job—we gave him a job.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1563" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1563" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1563" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1563" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES ALLEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I went with Mr. Price and the prisoner to the shop in the Westminster-bridge-road—we then went to a coffee shop, and the prisoner said, "You must go at seven o'clock for your money, I sold them for 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;"—I have worked for Mr. Price five months—I never heard of the prisoner being a partner—I have seen him paid his wages 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week—he worked for 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and I have seen him paid his wages.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1564" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1564" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1564" type="surname" value="REED"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1564" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN REED</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Mr. James Bedell. On the 28th of Oct., about five o'clock in the evening, the prisoner came with three washhand-stands—I went and spoke to Mr. Bedell about them—I bought them for 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I paid the prisoner, and have the receipt in his writing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1565" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1565" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1565" type="surname" value="TURPIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1565" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY TURPIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable G</hi> 119.) I took the prisoner—I told him it was for running away with the stands of Mr. Price—he said, "That is all right; it is three months ago."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I went to work for Mr. Price, and after some time my father was going to the Cape of Good Hope, and Price, not knowing the cabinet business, told me if I would take 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and board, lodging, and washing, I should share in the profits, as it was all my connexion; I said, "Very well;" if Mr. Stallybrass is here, he knows the bills were made out in my name; we drew two separate bills on a customer, and there is my name first on the bills; I paid them both to Mr. Stallybrass, and the bills were, "To Messrs. Griffiths, and L. and It. Price;" this was the only card I could get from a friend; the other cards were taken away, and the invoices and bills with my name on them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1566" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1566" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1566" type="surname" value="FICKLING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1566" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT FICKLING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a cabinet-maker, and have lived upwards of two years at No. 36, Brown's-lane, Spitalfields. I was employed by the prisoner—I was not then aware it was a partnership, but I understood three or four days afterwards that it was a partnership—the prisoner employed me—I worked piece work—I was employed in making washhand-standa I believe—I am sure I was, and I made dressing-tables—the same person employed me to do them—no other person employed me—the prisoner was the active man for the partnership concern as I understood—I was paid sometimes by Price, and sometimes by the prisoner—Robert Price said, "You must not suppose this is all Mr. Griffith's concern; I am the principal partner."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you sure he said these words, "I am the partner?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, his elder brother, Mr. Lemuel Price is the elder partner—he said, "It is ours"—his elder brother and his—I always understood the prisoner was partner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">ROBERT PRICE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know this witness? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, the prisoner has robbed him as well as me—he went with me and the constable to search the prisoner's lodging for his tools—he has been in constant inter<lb></lb>course with the prisoner—I never told him that it was not all Griffith's con<lb></lb>cern—I told him it was not Griffith's concern, but mine and my brother's—my brother and I have always been together, but he had nothing to do with this concern, it was mine—I am sure the washhand-stands were not my</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050235"></xptr>
               <p>brother's, they were mine—he had nothing to do with them—I distinctly swear the prisoner was no partner of mine in any way—I paid the work-people, but sometimes if I was out the prisoner might do it—I gave him the money to pay the men—these cards with the prisoner's name I never saw—he had no share in any way—when he wanted clothes I ordered them, and paid for them, and put them down to his account—the washhand-stands were made in Oct.—I was married in June—before I was married my brother and I divided the cabinet work, but after I was married he gave it up to me—I attended to it, and he had none of the profits of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I took on both Fickling and Hanley; previous to my leaving I had been very ill, and subject to fits, and they said that they had got a lawyer to draw up a paper, and I was to sign it that I had no claim on the concern; Mr. Henley told me of it.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18440205-813-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
